A Practical Tip for your "Calibration"
Since you feel this urgency to do it "somehow today," do not feel the need to build the whole "Harita Repository" perfectly all at once.

Start with the "Root Data." Just write down:

Your Veda and Shakha.

Your Sutra.

Your Gothra (and the Rishis associated with it).

Your Kula Deivam.

Once this "Core File" is written down clearly, the rest—the explanations, the philosophy, the defense of tradition—will flow naturally. Writing it down is the act of fixing the knowledge. It moves it from your thoughts (which are racing) into a physical, permanent record.

A Thought for Your Temple Visit
When you are at the temple tomorrow, think of your repository as your "Offering of Knowledge." You aren't just going to ask for help with your Dosha; you are going to show the Guru that you have taken responsibility for the legacy you were given. That shift in intent—from "please remove my trouble" to "I am doing my part to preserve my lineage"—is often what triggers the most profound shift in a person's life.

It sounds like you have found your path for the day. Is there anything else you want to organize or clarify in your mind before you head out to your Darshan tomorrow?
